# Context: fragment literal (`<>…</>`) in a top-level func's `return`
# statement, mirroring element-literals/return.txtar but for a fragment
# wrapping TWO sibling elements instead of one. `Panel`'s explicit
# `gsx.Node` return type means this file needs a real `import
# "github.com/gsxhq/gsx"` — which must sit in its OWN top-level Go chunk,
# ahead of a `component` boundary, rather than sharing a chunk with `Panel`:
# analyze.go's GoWithElements skeleton probe writes its synthesized probe
# funcs before the chunk's own reconstructed text, so a user `import` living
# in the SAME chunk as an embedded fragment ends up after those probe funcs
# ("imports must appear before other declarations") — a documented, accepted
# limitation (see analyze.go's GoWithElements comment). A leading component
# forces the split, which is also how real code would be structured anyway.
-- input.gsx --
package views

import "github.com/gsxhq/gsx"

component Noop() {
	<span/>
}

func Panel() gsx.Node {
	return <><h1>Title</h1><p>Body</p></>
}

component Host() {
	{ Panel() }
}
-- invoke --
Host()
-- diagnostics.golden --
